{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-ac59151f5b71c502", "type": "tool_result", "content": "Title: GitHub - gedeonmate/conversation-timing · GitHub\nREADME preview: Conversational Timing Results for ASR Simulation This repository is a compact companion package for the paper \"On the Role of Conversational Timing in Synthetic Training Data for ASR\" available on arXiv: link The paper studies conversational timing as a controllable training-data variable for multi-speaker ASR. Synthetic conversations are generated from a low-dimensional exponential-tilting family over pause and overlap timing distributions. The timing parameter space is explored with Latin hypercube sampling (LHS) followed by multi-objective Bayesian optimization (BO), and each sampled configuration is evaluated by downstream concatenated-permutation WER and CER ( cpWER , cpCER ) on BEA-Dialogue development and evaluation splits. This repo collects the result figures and compact tables that are most useful as a paper supplement. It is intentionally not a full analysis dump. Main Takeaways Timing statistics explain ASR behavior more directly than raw simulator coordinates. On the evalu", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "48fbb187-5924-404f-8026-eca35097d118", "uuid": "a7165c06-d801-405e-9cae-c485a01828d1", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T14:18:37.886Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "Title: GitHub - gedeonmate/conversation-timing · GitHub\nREADME preview: Conversational Timing Results for ASR Simulation This repository is a compact companion package for the paper \"On the Role of Conversational Timing in Synthetic Training Data for ASR\" available on arXiv: link The paper studies conversational timing as a controllable training-data variable for multi-speaker ASR. Synthetic conversations are generated from a low-dimensional exponential-tilting family over pause and overlap timing distributions. The timing parameter space is explored with Latin hypercube sampling (LHS) followed by multi-objective Bayesian optimization (BO), and each sampled configuration is evaluated by downstream concatenated-permutation WER and CER ( cpWER , cpCER ) on BEA-Dialogue development and evaluation splits. This repo collects the result figures and compact tables that are most useful as a paper supplement. It is intentionally not a full analysis dump. Main Takeaways Timing statistics explain ASR behavior more directly than raw simulator coordinates. On the evalu", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
